An individual's immediate social and relational milieu in which they grow up may have a substantial influence on their educational results. According to research, variables such as family structure, poverty, and community resources may all have a substantial impact on an individual's educational experiences and results. Children from single-parent families, for example, have poorer school success and graduation rates than children from two-parent households, according to study. This may be due to a variety of causes, including a lack of emotional and financial support from a second parent, as well as a lack of role models with higher levels of education. Poverty may also have a detrimental influence on academic performance. Low-income children are more likely to attend schools with less resources and less experienced instructors, which may contribute to poorer academic attainment. They may also lack access to technology, extracurricular activities, and instructional resources, all of which are necessary for a decent education. Additionally, an individual's parents' level of education and money might influence their educational success. Children with higher levels of education and money are more likely to have positive educational experiences and results, owing to greater access to resources and opportunities. The culture and area in which a person grows up might also influence their educational success. Children who grow up in high-crime regions with limited access to community facilities like libraries and parks may have less chances to study and face greater obstacles in school. Overall, an individual's immediate social, relational milieu in which they grow up may have a substantial influence on their educational results. Family structure, poverty, and community resources may all impact an individual's educational experiences and opportunities, and hence their academic success. 